Here's a minimal API endpoint handling multipart form uploads with images + a description:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o => o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Ensure it's a form submission
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart/form-data request.");

    var form = await request.ReadFormAsync();

    var description = form["description"].ToString();
    var files = form.Files.GetFiles("images");

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No image files provided.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var dest = Path.Combine("uploads", $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}");
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(dest);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(dest);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, fileCount = saved.Count, paths = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()                          // needed for form POSTs without a token
.WithName("UploadImages");

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **`ConfigureKestrel`** raises the default ~30 MB body limit to 50 MB.
- **`ReadFormAsync`** parses the `multipart/form-data`; `form["description"]` gets the text field, `form.Files.GetFiles("images")` gets all files under that field name.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** is required in .NET 8+ minimal APIs for form endpoints without an antiforgery token.

**Test with `curl`:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "description=My vacation photos" \
  -F "images=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "images=@photo2.png"
```

If you'd rather use a **strongly-typed model** instead of raw `HttpRequest`, you can bind directly:

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload-typed", async (
    [FromForm] string description,
    IFormFileCollection images) =>
{
    // same logic as above
});
```

This requires the `[FromForm]` attribute (new in .NET 8) and matching form field names.
